solutions.content:
The first solution I came up with involves using an integer to build up the result in. Along with another integer to indicate the shift needed at the current bit being inspected.

On each iteration of the loop, check if the bit in the ones place is set. If so you will OR that bit shifted by the needed amount for that iteration to the result. Then you will shift the overall number to the right and increment the shift count for the next iteration.

The loop will then terminate once the number has reached 0. So the loop will execute once for each bit up until the most significant bit. Meaning it is O(n) in time complexity relative to MSB.
```
public int findComplement(int num) {
    int a = 0;
    int pow = 0;
    while(num > 0){
        if((num & 1) == 0)
            a |= 1 << pow;
        num >>= 1;
        pow++;
    }
    return a;
}
```


The next solution I came up with relies on the fact that you can create the mask for the bits based on the length of the binary representation. Since Java provides a toBinaryString method the string can be used to find the binary length.

Once the length is known you can raise 2 to the power of the length. Then subtract one to create an integer mask with all bits set up to the most significant bit.

Then the XOR operator can be used to flip all bits that aren't alike in the mask and the number. Which is what the problem is asking for (since the mask is set to all ones).

Java's Integer.toBinaryString method runs in O(n) relative to the most significant bit. Similar in the way that the first solution was implemented. So therefore this also executes in O(n) overall time (however it can easily be made into a nice 1 liner).

```
public int findComplement(int num){
    int xor = (int) (Math.pow(2, Integer.toBinaryString(num).length()) - 1);
    return num ^ xor;
}
```


After this I began to realize this could easily turn into O(1) time complexity. Due to the maximum number of bits in an Integer is 32.

To do this I OR'd the number shifted to the right by 0 to 31. Resulting in a mask that contained all bits set from the most significant down. This time it executed exacly 32 times leading to O(32) = O(1) time complexity.

To get the result I then XOR the number to the mask. Which gets the resulting integer where all bits weren't set in the number given

```
public int findComplement(int num){
    int mask = 0;
    for(int i = 0; i < 32; i++)
        mask |= num >> i;
    return num ^ mask;
	}
```


Lastly I realized that by starting the mask equal to the number. The most significant bit of the number would also be the most significant in the mask.

From there I could shift the mask to the right by 1 and OR it on. This makes each set bit in the original number and the one to its immediate right set in the mask.

Now you can shift the bits in the mask by 2 to the right and OR it on. Thus making the original bit and the next 3 to its right set as well.

This doubling of set bits repeats up until the last shift of 16. Which will guarantee that all bits from the most significant down are set.

Once the mask has been created. The result is the found by XORing the mask to the original number as in the previous example.

```
public int findComplement(int num){
    int mask = num;
    mask |= mask >> 1;
    mask |= mask >> 2;
    mask |= mask >> 4;
    mask |= mask >> 8;
    mask |= mask >> 16;
    return num ^ mask;
}
```

