        for (int bit = 0; bit < 32; bit++) {
            int bits_1 = 0;
            for (int num : nums) {
                if ((num >> bit) & 1 == 1)
                    bits_1++;
            }
            res += bits_1 * (N - bits_1);
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

solutions.content:
It's easy to think about O(n^2) solution, but it has 99% chance to fail an interview. We have to find a better way. 

We know that hamming distance is a bitwise operation, if we can find a way to do those bitwise operation together instead of separate, we are good. 

We can use a 32 size array to reocrd number of occurance for each bits at index i (Because int type has 32 bits). we define an array dp, which means if we represent every number in binary, there are dp[i] numbers at index i is 1. For example, if input is (0100) (1110) (0010), then dp[0] = 1, dp[1] = 2, dp[2] = 2 and d[3] = 0. 

Because totally there are n numbers, we know at index i, there are dp[i] number is 1 and n - dp[i] number is 0. Thus for each j belongs to dp[i] and each k belongs to n - dp[i], the hamming distance of pair {j,k} at position i must be 1, and there are (n - dp[i]) * dp[i] pairs in total. If we repeat the process for each position i, we then find out the total hamming distance, which equals to sum of (n-dp[i]) * dp[i] for i = 0 : 31.

Here is the c++ codes. 
```
class Solution {
public:
    int totalHammingDistance(vector<int>& nums) {
        int dp[32] = {};
        for(int x : nums){
            bitset<32> b(x);
            for(int i = 0;i<b.size();i++){
                if(b[i]){
                    dp[i] += 1;
                }
            }
        }
        int ret = 0;
        int n = nums.size();
        for(auto x: dp){
            ret += (n - x) * x;
        }
        return ret;
    }
};
```

