solutions.content:
**The solution is as follows:**

Directly count the number of different bits across all bit positions.

First off keep track of the number of occurences of each bit values in each bit position using a frequency array its dimensions is (32, 2) (32 for each bit position, 2 for each bit value). 

For each bit position you can get the number of times this particular bit appears in the result is the number of occurences of bit value 0 multiplied by the number of occurences of bit value 1 and summing that up across all bit positions.

```
class Solution {
public:
    int totalHammingDistance(vector<int>& nums) {
        vector<vector<int>> util(32, vector<int>(2, 0));
        for (int i = 0; i < 32; ++i) {
            for (auto n : nums) {
                auto tmp = (n & (1 << i));
                util[i][tmp != 0]++;
            }
        }

        int nt = 0;

        for (auto tmp : util) {
            nt += tmp[0] * tmp[1];
        }

        return nt;
    }
};
```

**Another approach:**

1. Assume all the bits are different accross all the numbers and store the value in the answer variable.
2. Create a frequency array (same one as that in approach 1).
3. If a bit is repeated ```n``` times it is included in the answer ```n * (n - 1) / 2``` so we have to decrement that value from the answer variable.

Note: Use long long instead of int to prevent any overflow errors.
```
using ll = long long int;

class Solution {
public:
    int totalHammingDistance(vector<int>& nums) {
        vector<vector<int>> util(32, vector<int>(2, 0));
        for (int i = 0; i < 32; ++i) {
            for (auto n : nums) {
                auto tmp = (n & (1 << i));
                util[i][tmp != 0]++;
            }
        }

        ll n = nums.size(), nt = 32 * n * (n - 1) / 2;

        for (auto tmp : util) {
            nt -= tmp[0] * (tmp[0] - 1) / 2;
            nt -= tmp[1] * (tmp[1] - 1) / 2;
        }

        return int(nt);
    }
};
```

