solutions.content:
Hamming distance between a even and odd number is at least 1 because the last bit is always different (even number has 0 and odd number has 1).

So just find the number of even and odd numbers in the array. If there are 2 even numbers and 3 odd numbers, the minimum total hamming distance is 6.

Doing it once will give the minimum hamming distance of the last bits in all the numbers. To find for the remaining bits, divide all the numbers by 2 and continue doing it.

Keep continuing this till all the numbers in the array are 0.

Since our terminating point is when all the numbers are 0, and we move towards the terminating point by dividing all the numbers by 2, the highest number will be the last number to reach 0 and we would have divided the numbers log(highestNumber) times to reach 0.

So the complexity is O(nlogk) where k is the highest number in the array.

```
class Solution {
    public int totalHammingDistance(int[] nums) {
        int count = 0;

        while(true){
            int numEven = 0;
            int numOdd = 0;
            int numZero = 0;
            for(int i=0; i<nums.length; i++) {
                if(nums[i] == 0) numZero++;
                if(nums[i] % 2 == 0) {
                    numEven++;
                } else {
                    numOdd++;
                }
                nums[i] = nums[i]/2;
            }

            if(numZero == nums.length) break;

            count += numEven*numOdd;
        }
        return count;
    }
}
```

