### Trivial Solution:
**Time Complexity**: O(n ^ 2), n is the length of array.
```cpp
class Solution {
    int getNumXOR(int l, int r)  {
        int k = l ^ r, res = 0;
        while(k) {
            res += k & 1;
            k >>= 1;
        }
        return res;
    }
public:
    int totalHammingDistance(vector<int>& nums) {
        int res = 0;
        const int len = nums.size();
        for (int i = 0; i < len; ++i) {
            for (int j = i + 1; j < len; ++j) {
                res += getNumXOR(nums[i], nums[j]);
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```
It cannot pass the big test case.
### Optimized Solution:
**Time Complexity:** O(n), n is the length of array.

We don't really need to compare every two pair of integers. In the trivial solution, it actually collects more information than we need: it gives us the number of different bits for every pair of integers. And we only need to know the total number of different bits for all pairs of integers.

To get rid of the redundant information, we can **multiple** the number of ones and zeros for every bit from 1 to 32 instead of comparing every pair of integers.

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int totalHammingDistance(vector<int>& nums) {
        int ones = 0, sum = 0;
        const int len = nums.size();
        for (int i = 0; i < 32; ++i) {
            ones = 0;
            for (int val: nums)
                ones += val >> i & 1;
            sum += (len - ones) * ones;
        }
        return sum;
    }
};
```

